After taking this course, students will be able to:

• understand on-site data collection skills and field techniques;

• interpret geographical issues from urban and rural settings;

• enhance group-work ability and team spirit.

Guangdong-Hong Kong-Macao Greater Bay Area is a rapidly growing and significant mega-city region in the world. This course will not only offer a broad coverage on various aspects of Hong Kong, Macao and the PRD development, but also place an emphasis on the intricate relationship of the three places. After completing the course, students will be able to:

* describe the historical development of Hong Kong, Macao and the PRD;

* explain why Hong Kong, Macao and the PRD are closely related and intermingled under the rapid process of globalization;

* use examples to show how a place’s growth and development is associated with regional and global conditions;

* relate knowledge to potential employment in the future;

* diagnose the social, economic and environmental problems of the region beyond what is presented in the mass media.

After taking this course, students are expected to:

1. gain the basic knowledge of human geography and understand the processes and patterns of urban and economic development across the globe;
2. understand global-local interactions and their impacts on our daily life in the era of globalization;
3. develop the capability to associate world development with local development issues; and

4. become aware of local specific development trajectories in human geographical perspectives.

• To understand the broad coverage, diversity and interdisciplinarity of geography and resource management as subject areas;
• To understand the inter-relationships between human and physical geography at different geographical scales;
• To integrate and apply various theories and tools to investigate human-environment relationships in space, place and time;
• To motivate students to think critically and geographically by assessing information, facts and ideas related to resources, society and environment;
• To facilitate students to navigate through the major programme in geography and resource management.

Field studies will provide students an opportunity to understand real-world situations and to supplement the lectures. After taking the course, students will be able to:

