After successfully completing this course, the students will be able to:

1. Evaluate the conflicting views on the reasons for the lack of a more sustainable development;
2. Analyze where the solutions may lay for SDGs, and the economic, social and environmental constraints to the adoption of these solutions;
3. Students will be able to understand and describe cognitive, socio-economic and behavioural aspects of sustainable development, and
4. Comprehend the skills necessary to interpret the policies of governments and international organisations.

On successful completion of this course, the student will be able to:

• outline key ideas used by geographers in understanding natural resource management issues;
• understand how natural processes are influencing natural resource management;
• acquire knowledge related to physical earth resource, biotic and ecological resource and socio-cultural aspects of natural resource management;
• develop an understanding and skills necessary for management of natural and man-made resources;
• enhance research skills, with a focus on problem solving.

Students are expected to understand the concept of smart cities and the key components of smart cities, especially those related to Hong Kong’s smart cities blueprint. More importantly, students are encouraged to take part in the building and managing smart cities in future to make our cities more livable and sustainable. After taking this course, students should be able to:

1. Understand the rise of smart cities;
2. Understand the main pillars of smart cities;
3. Describe how technology and innovation affect cities and our daily lives;
4. Become familiar with the latest practice of smart cities in Hong Kong;
5. Summarize the emerging theories of smart cites;
6. Develop critical thinking on the practice and goals of smart cities.

