Students are expected to develop a comprehensive understanding and practical experience about conducting scientific research in geography. Both the overall framework design and specific procedural techniques will be discussed to enable students to master the essential steps in research and understand the rationale behind them. After completing the course, students will be able to:

• identify the nature and process of scientific research in geography;
• use library resources critically and effectively;
• recognize the use of different theories to explain daily issues from different geographical perspectives;
• plan a research activity with logical procedures and allocate all resources effectively;
• develop the sensitivity to conduct research scientifically and ethically and to conduct data collection in the field safely;
• analyse both qualitative and quantitative data;
• present research findings in an academic style and manage a research project independently or collectively, starting from the generation of a research topic to the ending with a research report.

After completion of this course, students should:
• acquire a basic knowledge of earth materials, their origin and weathering characteristics;
• know the structure, origin, and time relationship of landforms;
• understand the mechanisms by which geomorphic processes create landforms; and
• develop skills of landform description

On successful completion of this course, the student will be able to:

• Outline key ideas used by geographers in studying and understanding the tourism industry;
• Understand the social, cultural, economic and environmental aspects of tourism planning and management;
• Acquire knowledge on tourism impacts at destinations;
• Develop and apply methodologies for investigating, evaluating and planning tourism in various environments

• Enhance research skills, with a focus on problem solving in the tourism industry

• They will be able to articulate scientific information in detail, and reinforce their generic skills like communication and presentation

Upon completion of this course, the student should be able to

- understand basic ideas of sustainable development in relation to transport development and planning;
- grasp concepts and use basic research tools to analyze transport problems in a geographic context;
- identify important transport issues/problems at different geographical scales and develop a perspective to analyze transport-related problems;
- understand basic concepts of international logistics and factors affecting the formation of logistics centers; and

- appreciate the role of transportation in socio-economic contexts.

At the end of the course, students are expected to be able to:

1. Capture basic concepts and theories of development and grasp the measurement and indicators of development;
2. Understand development challenges and constraints facing the developing world and evaluate policies that have been implemented in different countries;
3. Develop the ability to analyze and debate various contemporary issues in world development; and
4. Enhance capabilities in various skills such as critical thinking, communication skills, data analysis, essay writing and self-managed learning through various learning activities which include in-class discussion, weekly reading, case studies, field trips and tutorials.

After completing the courses, students should be able to:
• Develop valid research questions through identifying research gaps in the course of thorough literature review;
• Synthesise specific geographical and resource management knowledge through independent and in-depth investigation and research;
• Develop skills and capability of applying a wide range of geography and resource management research methods;
• Critically analyse and organise primary and secondary data logically to present coherent arguments; and
• Refine skills such as critical thinking, problem solving, data management, communication and presentation.

After taking this course, students will be able:

• To synthesize and analyse cutting edge knowledge in geography and resource management;
• To consider and reflect on the applicability of the new knowledge in different geographical scales;
• To advance and develop their geographical skills; and

• To extract and generate values and principles from the geographical knowledge learned for life-long practice and learning.

