After completing this course, students should be able to:

• recognise smart city development as a complex political project;
• explain the links between cities and technological innovation through appropriate social theories;
• identify the key policies for promoting and managing smart city development;
• analyse the pros and cons of smart city development for urban economic, environmental and social governance; and

• evaluate and compare the performance of smart city initiatives of different cities.

By the end of the course, students are expected to be able to:

* Understand the value of geography as an academic discipline in the physical and social sciences;
* Master the basic elements of a good geographical research project;
* Demonstrate the analytical skills in developing clear and logical research arguments, as well as the communication skills in disseminating their research findings; and
* Develop the confidence to succeed in their graduate studies.

Many geographical studies and researches use various quantitative analyses which try to find out the real situations. Statistical analysis is one of the widely used quantitative methods. The course will introduce various multivariate statistical techniques commonly employed by geographers and researchers in allied fields. After taking the course, students will be able to:

1. Distinguish different statistical models;
2. Recognize the assumptions of various statistical models;
3. Understand statistical methods and their procedures;
4. Perform statistical analyses using computer; and

5. Evaluate and interpret the results of various statistical models.
